    overview: "Immunoglobulins (antibodies) are glycoproteins produced by plasma cells. Five classes (isotypes) defined by heavy chain type: IgG (gamma), IgA (alpha), IgM (mu), IgE (epsilon), IgD (delta). Each has distinct structure, distribution, and function. Understanding their properties is fundamental to immunology and serology testing in the clinical laboratory.",
    mechanismPhysiology: "Basic structure: 2 heavy chains + 2 light chains (kappa or lambda) linked by disulfide bonds. Fab region (antigen-binding fragment) contains variable regions. Fc region (crystallizable fragment) mediates effector functions (complement activation, opsonization, placental transfer). IgG: monomer, 4 subclasses (IgG1-4), most abundant in serum (~75%). IgA: dimer in secretions (secretory IgA with J-chain + secretory component), monomer in serum. IgM: pentamer with J-chain (largest Ig). IgE: monomer (lowest serum concentration). IgD: monomer (on B-cell surface with IgM).",
