    signsSymptoms: "Immunoglobulin testing is ordered for: suspected immunodeficiency (recurrent infections), monoclonal gammopathy (M-spike on SPEP—myeloma, Waldenstrom), IgA deficiency (most common primary immunodeficiency, ~1:500), allergic conditions (elevated IgE), chronic infections (polyclonal hypergammaglobulinemia).",
    assessment: "Quantification: nephelometry or turbidimetry for IgG, IgA, IgM. SPEP (serum protein electrophoresis): monoclonal band (M-spike) in gamma region suggests myeloma or lymphoproliferative disorder. Immunofixation (IFE): identifies heavy chain and light chain type of M-spike. Free light chains (kappa/lambda ratio): sensitive marker for light chain myeloma and amyloidosis. IgE: measured by specific immunoassay (RAST/ImmunoCAP for allergen-specific IgE).",
    management: "IgA deficiency: most common primary immunodeficiency (~1:500 prevalence). Patients at risk for ANAPHYLAXIS if transfused with IgA-containing blood products (if they have anti-IgA antibodies). Use washed RBCs or IgA-deficient donor products. Selective IgA deficiency may have false-positive TTGA (tissue transglutaminase IgA) for celiac screening—use IgG-based celiac testing. Waldenstrom macroglobulinemia: IgM monoclonal gammopathy with hyperviscosity symptoms.",
    complications: "Monoclonal gammopathy: M-protein may interfere with laboratory assays (coagulation, chemistry). Cryoglobulins (immunoglobulins that precipitate at cold temperatures) may cause sample clotting artifacts. Rouleaux formation from elevated immunoglobulins interferes with blood banking testing. Bence Jones protein (free light chains in urine) detected by urine protein electrophoresis, NOT by dipstick (dipstick detects albumin primarily).",
    clinicalPearls: ["IgG is the ONLY immunoglobulin that crosses the placenta—provides neonatal passive immunity", "IgM is the LARGEST Ig (pentamer) and MOST efficient at complement activation", "IgA is the predominant mucosal antibody—found in secretions (saliva, tears, breast milk)", "IgA deficiency: most common primary immunodeficiency; risk of anaphylaxis with blood transfusion if anti-IgA present"],
    examPitfalls: ["IgM does NOT cross the placenta—if IgM is detected in a neonate, it indicates fetal/neonatal ACTIVE infection", "Bence Jones protein (free light chains) is NOT detected by urine dipstick—need urine protein electrophoresis or heat test", "IgG4 does NOT activate complement (unlike IgG1, IgG2, IgG3)—this is commonly tested"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "Why is IgM most efficient at complement activation?", answer: "IgM is a pentamer with 10 antigen-binding sites. Complement activation via the classical pathway requires C1q to bind at least 2 Fc regions in close proximity. A single IgM pentamer provides 5 Fc regions in one molecule, easily satisfying this requirement. IgG is a monomer—requires 2 IgG molecules bound close together on the antigen surface to activate complement, which is less efficient." }, { question: "What is SPEP vs immunofixation?", answer: "SPEP (serum protein electrophoresis) separates serum proteins by charge: albumin, alpha-1, alpha-2, beta, gamma. A monoclonal spike (M-spike) in gamma region suggests monoclonal gammopathy. Immunofixation (IFE) identifies the specific heavy chain (IgG, IgA, IgM) and light chain (kappa, lambda) type of the M-protein. SPEP detects; IFE characterizes. Both are needed for complete evaluation." }]
